<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How many studs do I need for a wall?", answer: "For a basic field without corners or openings, use ceiling(wall length in inches ÷ spacing) + 1 studs. A 20 ft wall at 16\" OC needs 240 ÷ 16 = 15, plus one at the far end = 16 studs. Add 2 studs per L-corner, 3 per T-intersection, and 4 per door or window opening (2 jack + 2 king)." },
  { question: "What is 16 on center vs 24 on center?", answer: "Stud spacing measured center-to-center. 16\" OC is the most common residential standard — it keeps drywall joints landing on studs and is required by IRC for 2x4 framing in bearing walls. 24\" OC uses fewer studs and less wood, which qualifies for Advanced Framing Techniques that increase insulation in the wall cavity, but it requires 2x6 studs in most climates." },
  { question: "How much plate stock do I need?", answer: "A framed wall has three plates: one bottom plate and a doubled top plate. Plate stock equals 3 × the wall length. A 20 ft wall needs 60 linear feet of plate stock (two 10-ft pieces or one 20-ft piece for the bottom, and two 10-ft or one 20-ft piece for each top plate)." },
  { question: "How many studs go around a door or window?", answer: "Standard openings use 4 extra studs: 2 king studs that run full wall height on each side, and 2 jack studs (trimmers) that hold up the header. Wider openings may need double jacks on each side. The header itself is a separate piece cut to the opening width plus 3 inches." },
  { question: "Should I buy extra studs?", answer: "Yes — order 5 to 10 percent more than calculated. Expect some crooked studs, cracks, and knots that you will cut off or cull. Precut studs (92-5/8\") save cutting time for 8 ft walls. For 9 ft walls, order 10 ft studs and cut. Lumber is cheaper than a return trip to the yard mid-framing." }
]) %>

